HEADWORD: Estop
<hw>Es*top"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Estophed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Estopping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF.
<ets>estoper</ets> to stop, plug, close, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧touper</ets>,
LL. <ets>stuppare</ets> to close with tow, obstruct, fr. L.
<ets>stuppa</ets> tow, oakum, cf. Gr. <grk>sty`pph</grk>. Cf.
<er>Stop</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To impede or bar by
estoppel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A party will be <qex>estopped</qex> by his admissions, where his
intent is to influence another, or derive an advantage to himself.</q>
<rj><qau>Abbott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Estoppel</ent>⟦br⟧
